<HEADLINE> NBA Declines to Meet Face to Face with Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The NBA league told its
players union yesterday it will not agree to another face-to-face
bargaining session until the union submits a final offer in
writing to the league's labor relations committee.
</P>
<P>
The union declined, according to Jeffrey Kessler, its outside
counsel.
</P>
<P>
"That's not the way to negotiate in good faith," Kessler
said."It's too late for posturing and game playing. The parties
need to get together and reach a deal."
</P>
<P>
The league has set a January 7 deadline to cut a deal with its
players, who have been locked out for six months, or the season
likely will be canceled.
</P>
<P>
Yesterday's standoff developed after union chief Billy Hunter
and NBA commissioner David Stern talked by phone in early
afternoon, according to both sides.
</P>
<P>
Kessler said Hunter sought to convene the two sides'
bargaining committees for a final session before the January 7
deadline. Short of that, Hunter suggested he meet with either
Stern or deputy commissioner Russ Granik, both of whom are on
vacation in other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
To expedite matters, Hunter and Stern agreed to have Jeffrey
Mishkin, the NBA's chief legal officer who is in New York, call
Kessler.
</P>
<P>
Mishkin said he asked Kessler how he would deliver the final
proposal. Kessler said he told Mishkin the proposal wasn't quite
ready, but that he would be available to meet within the hour.
</P>
<P>
"I said, 'We've already given you our final offer,'" Mishkin
said. "There's nothing really to talk about. We'll pass it along
to the labor relations committee. I see no reason to meet since
you rejected our last offer.'"
</P>
<P>
Mishkin said he assured Kessler that the union's final
proposal, if submitted, would be considered by the full board of
governors at its January 7 meeting.
</P>
<P>
Stern tipped his strategy for yesterday's decision in
conference call with reporters Monday when he said the labor
relations committee, composed of eight owners, had rejected a
face-to-face meeting, but the 29 governors would consider
anything the union wished to submit in writing.
</P>
<P>
The union is seeking a restoration of the league's middle
class in salaries, less restrictive free agency than the league
has proposed during nine months of negotiations and the same
share of league revenues as it received last season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
