<HEADLINE> Hun Sen Does Not Oppose Trying Khmer Rouge Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PEHN, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Prime Minister Hun
Sen said Friday that he is not opposed to the trial of Khmer Rouge
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen made the remarks in a statement broadcast on a local TV
Friday evening, which were seen as being directed at those who
opposed the government decision to welcome the recent defection
of Khmer Rouge leaders Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that his position on the trial of Khmer Rouge
leaders has not changed and will not change. At the same time, he
stressed that the trial of the Khmer Rouge should continue.
</P>
<P>
"I did not mention the trial of the Khmer Rouge leaders in my
recent talks, not because I have forgot it, but because I believed
the first thing we should talk about is peace, which is the most
need of the country and the Cambodian people," Hun Sen explained.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hun Sen said "Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea do not
need an amnesty before their defection, because they were not
convicted by any court or received any arrest warrant."
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen pointed out that the pair gave up their anti-government
struggles and returned to the society voluntarily, so they should
not be arrested. "We should not put all those who oppose the
government into the prison, instead to encourage them to
participate in the national construction," he said.
</P>
<P>
Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea defected to the royal government on
December 25 with assurances they would not be prosecuted. They
also received a warm welcome from Hun Sen when they arrived in
Phnom Penh and held nearly three-hours of talks with the prime
minister in his residence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
