<HEADLINE> Tanzania Needs $91 Million to Buy Emergency Food Supplies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania needs some 91.1million U.S.
 Dollars to buy emergency food supplies to augment the country's grain
stock in the first half of 1999, the central bank predicted Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to a monthly economic review report issued by the Bank of
Tanzania (BoT), the Strategic Grain Reserve (SGR) stood at 45,557 tons by
the end of last November, hitting the lowest level since it was set up in
1991.
</P>
<P>
The report largely attributed the shortage of food to floods caused
by El Nino phenomenon during 1997 and 1998, to insufficient short rains
during
the October and November last year, as well as to destructive pests.
</P>
<P>
Most of the country is suffering from a severe drought, except for
Kigoma Region in the west and some parts of the Lake Zone in the north
which have received some short rains.
</P>
<P>
President Benjamin Mkapa announced Thursday that the country has waived
maize import duty as a measure to deal with the food shortage situation.
</P>
<P>
In his New Year message to the nation Thursday night, Mkapa said the
country is short of 400,000 to 450,000 tons of food, or 25 to 30
percent below requirement.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa also encouraged businessmen to transport food from harvest regions
to grain deficit areas in the country, ordered local brewers not to use
food crops for production, and asked people not to be choosy about food,
saying cassava, plantain and yams should be consumed as well.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa advised people to prepare their farms as soon as possible and
plant drought resistant crops such as cassava and millets, adding that
valleys and lower basins should be used for crops cultivation.
</P>
<P>
BoT has predicted that overall inflation is expected to increase
gradually in the coming months on account of upward pressure on food prices
because of shortage in supplies of cereals, especially maize in the market.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Frederick Sumaye on Thursday evening cautioned
Tanzanians to be alert to counter the after effects of the current
drought which is likely to produce adverse impact on the country's
social and economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
