<DOCNO> XIE19990102.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Has No Interest in Escalating Tensions in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Chief of General Staff
Shaul Mofaz told reporters Friday that Israel has no interest in
escalating tensions in south Lebanon, denying reports that the
Israeli army will strike infrastructures in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Mofaz made the remarks just one day after Israeli security
cabinet warned of a harsh response to possible guerrilla attacks
on northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported earlier Friday that the security cabinet
has adopted an Israeli army proposal that if Hezbollah guerrillas
fire rocket into Israel, the army will respond by hitting targets,
mainly infrastructures such as power stations in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after a meeting held late Thursday
night, the security cabinet said Israel holds Beirut "directly
responsible" for what happened in south Lebanon, demanding that
the Lebanese government stem guerrilla activities there and
prevent rocket attacks on Israel.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet decision to punish Beirut for possible guerrilla
attacks drew criticism from the opposition Friday. They said the
decision will spark another war between Israel and Lebanon which
will cause heavy loss of lives.
</P>
<P>
Former Israeli prime minister Shimon Peres said only diplomatic
solutions can resolve the current conflict in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Uzi Landau, a far rightist legislator, however, said the
cabinet decision was not harsh enough. If an attack on Lebanon's
infrastructure is not effective, he said, he will recommend an
escalation of Israeli strike against Lebanese military forces.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a self-declared security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
As Israeli casualties mounted in south Lebanon, the wisdom of
Israel's military presence there has become a contentious issue in
the country. Twenty-two Israeli soldiers were killed in the zone
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Many Israelis demand a unilateral withdrawal from south
Lebanon, arguing that the 15-kilometer-deep buffer zone, has
failed to provide security for northern Israel but become a source
of conflicts instead.
</P>
<P>
This view was driven home when Hezbollah guerrillas fired a
barrage of Katysusha rockets into northern Israel last week,
wounding 13 people, to retaliate the killing of a Lebanese woman
and six of her children in an Israeli bombing raid the previous
day.
</P>
<P>
But the Israeli government has conditioned a withdrawal on a
security arrangement with Beirut, saying a unilateral pullout will
expose its north to Hezbollah fires and endanger the future of
Israel's local militia allies, the South Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and its main ally, Syria, have rejected Israel's
proposal, insisting that Israel withdraw from southern Lebanon
unconditionally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
