<HEADLINE> Yeltsin on Russia's Foreign Policy for 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
has outlined the main tasks of the Russian Foreign Ministry in
1999, the Itar-Tass news agency reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the New Year Yeltsin said these tasks include
stepping up integration in the Commonwealth of Independent States.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov told journalists that the tasks
also include the non-proliferation of weapons of mass destruction,
as well as Russia's role in the settlement of crises in Kosovo and
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about these conflicts, Ivanov pointed out the greatest
challenge here is to find a political formula for settling the
conflict within Yugoslavia, and to fully implement the U.N.
Security Council resolutions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The use of force will not help, Ivanov stressed, and will only
aggravate the situation.
</P>
<P>
The last task named by the president calls for invigorating
relations with European countries, primarily those in the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said that Russia attaches a great importance to the
Russian-U.S. dialogue as an important factor of stability in the
world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Russia will also develop relations with Asian partners,
primarily China, India and Japan, the minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
