<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Railway Starts to Transfer Goods to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The first cargo train carrying
goods for central Asian states left Iran's southern port city of
Bandar Shahid Rajai in Hormozgan province Friday.
</P>
<P>
The train with 50 wagons carried tea, furniture and other goods
from the port city close to the provincial capital of Bandar Abbas
directly to the border city of Sarakhs with Turkmenistan, the
Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Abbas Fathollahi, director general of the railway in Hormozgan
province, said in a ceremony that Iran will dispatch a train of 50
wagons every Friday to transfer 4,000 tonnes of goods to Central
Asian states.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iranian railway has the capability to dispatch 50
wagons of goods every day from Shahid Rajai to Sarakhs, adding
that Iran can earn a transportation fee as much as the value of
300 barrels of oil from each wagon.
</P>
<P>
The railroad connecting Sarakhs and Bandar Abbas was
inaugurated in 1995, an important project for transferring
imported and exported goods of the land-locked Central Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
Fathollahi said that from March 20, the beginning of the
current Iranian calendar year, the Iranian railway has
transferred 250,000 tonnes of exported cotton from the Central
Asian countries to Bandar Rajai, registering a rise of 300
percent compared with the same period of last Iranian year.
</P>
<P>
Iran has announced Bandar Rajai as a special economic zone to
encourage foreign companies to transfer goods from and to the
Central Asian countries through the port city.
</P>
<P>
Director General of Ports and Navigation of the province Ali
Estiri also said at the ceremony that Iran has opened 10
international transportation lines to transfer goods directly from
Bandar Rajai special zone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
