<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tension over S-300 Missiles to Continue: Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkish State Minister Sukru
Sina Gurel said Friday that the tension that erupted in the
region over the controversy surrounding the Russian-made S-300
missiles would continue.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that Greece and Greek Cyprus do not rule out the
possibility of using the missiles means that the tension in the
region will continue," the semi-official Anatolia News Agency
quoted Gurel as saying at a winter resort in Uludag mountains near
western province of Bursa.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish minister reiterated Ankara's determination not to
allow the S-300 missiles issue to be manipulated as a bargaining
chip against Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides announced Tuesday that he
had decided not to deploy the S-300 missiles in Cyprus and would
negotiate with Russia on possible deployment of the missiles
on the Greek island of Crete.
</P>
<P>
Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis said at the same day that
his country supported Clerides' decision.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus struck the missile deal with Russia in January 1997, in
a bid to cement its air defense capability.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, the close ally of independence-seeking Turkish Cypriots
in northern Cyprus, has threatened to launch preemptive strikes
on the missiles if they are brought to the divided island.
</P>
<P>
The arrival of the missiles in Cyprus has already been put off
several times under Turkish and international pressures.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriots-controlled
south and the Turkish Cypriots-dominated north after Turkey
landed its troops and took over the northern third of the country
in 1974 in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
