<DOCNO> XIE19990102.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RAMALLAH -- Aid to the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) fell
in 1998 compared with the year before, according to the
Palestinian Ministry of Planning and International Cooperation,
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the drop to internal reasons of donor
states and obstacles planted by Israel to hinder certain projects,
Arabic daily Al Hayat reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The donor countries pledged at their Washington conference last
November to provide some 3 billion U.S. dollars to the PNA over
the coming five years.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Yemen expected higher unemployment rate in 1999 to
reach 32 percent. The number of the jobless will reach 1.1 million.
</P>
<P>
A recent Yemeni parliamentary report said that about 831,000
people, or 20.8 percent, of the labour force were out of work in
1998, Arabic-language newspaper Al Hayat reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Yemen decided last October to suspend employment temporarily in
government offices except the sectors of education, health and
services.
</P>
<P>
A recent employment survey conducted by the Civil Service
Ministry, in collaboration with the World Bank, revealed that the
number of civil servants is 415,000, 75 percent of whom are
employed by three ministries, namely, Health, Education, and
Construction and Housing.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon earned a total of 750 billion Lebanese pounds
(about 500 million dollars) from post and telecommunications
services in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"The ministry (of post and telecommunications) has transferred
around 410 billion pounds (about 270 million dollars) to the
Treasury and used the rest to cover the salaries of ministry
staff and maintenance expenditures," the Daily Star quoted the
minister, Issam Naaman, as saying on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Naaman said his ministry will move from being the second
highest source of government revenue to the first in
1999. Lebanon's customs is the highest revenue earner.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The first cargo train carrying goods for central
Asian states left Iran's southern port city of Bandar Shahid Rajai
in Hormozgan province Friday.
</P>
<P>
The train with 50 wagons carried tea, furniture and other goods
from the port city close to the provincial capital of Bandar Abbas
directly to the border city of Sarakhs with Turkmenistan, the
Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Abbas Fathollahi, director general of the railway in Hormozgan
province, said in a ceremony that Iran will dispatch a train of 50
wagons every Friday to transfer 4,000 tonnes of goods to Central
Asian states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
