<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2100 GMT, January 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's security cabinet has decided to hold the
Lebanese government responsible for any rocket attacks on northern
Israel launched by Hezbollah guerillas, virtually rejecting a
unilateral withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting late Thursday night, the inner cabinet adopted an
Israeli army proposal that it will respond to any Katyusha rocket
attack on Israel by hitting a target in Lebanon, Israel Radio
reported Friday. (BC-Israel-Lebanon)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- In a rare move, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
lashed out at the Iraqi government and President Saddam Hussein
for failing to "play the necessary role" in easing the
long-running plight of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi papers, known to be controlled by the government, have
reportedly blamed Arab leaders, including Mubarak, for failing to
help Iraq have the U.N. sanctions lifted while Egypt's official
media accused Saddam himself of bringing about the disasters in
Iraq and causing the rift in Arab ranks by sending troops into
Kuwait. (BC-Egypt-Iraq-Criticism)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Chief of General Staff Shaul Mofaz told
reporters Friday that Israel has no interest in escalating
tensions in south Lebanon, denying reports that the Israeli army
will strike infrastructures in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Mofaz made the remarks just one day after Israeli security
cabinet warned of a harsh response to possible guerrilla attacks
on northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported earlier Friday that the security cabinet
has adopted an Israeli army proposal that if Hezbollah guerrillas
fire rocket into Israel, the army will respond by hitting targets,
mainly infrastructures such as power stations in Lebanon.
(BC-Israel-Lebanon)
</P>
