<HEADLINE> China's Spring City Sees Snow at New Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, January 2 (Xinhua) -- China's "Spring City", Kunming,
got a rare and unexpected sight of snow today, bringing jubilation
to local residents during their New Year celebrations.
</P>
<P>
The snow caused little inconvenience to local traffic, however,
as the snowflakes quickly melted after hitting the ground, and no
snow-related traffic accidents have been reported.
</P>
<P>
The capital of southwest China's Yunnan Province, Kunming has
spring-like weather year round because of its special topography,
with an average annual temperature of 14.5 degrees centigrade.
</P>
<P>
Kunming had its last snowfall in 1983 when more than 10
centimeters of thick snow covered the roads, according to one
taxi driver.
</P>
<P>
The local meteorological department attributed the rare snow to
cool air blowing down from Siberia, and said the temperature is
expected to rise again tomorrow.  
</P>
</TEXT>
