<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estonia Halts Water Supply to Russian City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Estonia Saturday stopped water
supply to and treatment of sewage from neighboring Ivangorod, of
Russia's Leningrad region, due to a debt of 1.5 million U.S.
dollars, news agencies reported.
</P>
<P>
Ivangorod has switched to its own water supply system but may
have to discharge the city's sewage to the Narva River, which
falls into the Gulf of Finland, threatening an environmental
disaster.
</P>
<P>
Ivangorod and Narva used to share water intake and sewage
treatment facilities in Soviet times. After the Soviet Union
collapsed in 1991, Estonia has been supplying Ivangorod with water
on a contract basis.
</P>
<P>
This was the second time for the Estonian Narva Vesi company to
stop water supply to Ivangorod.
</P>
<P>
On November 10, Narva Vesi cut off water supply to the Russian
city for the first time, forcing the local government to
contemplate evacuating the city's 10,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
The Russian and Estonian governments agreed then that Narva
Vesi would continue to meet 25 percent of the city's daily water
need under a contract that expired on December 31.
</P>
<P>
Water supply was further cut to 5 percent in December,
Itar-Tass said.
</P>
<P>
Narva Vesi said it sent a draft new contract to the Ivangorod
administration in early December, but had not received any
feedback.
</P>
<P>
Ivangorod consumes 6,800 cubic meters of water each day. The
daily amount of sewage exceeds 8,000 cubic meters, Interfax said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
