<HEADLINE> Pakistani Foreign Secretary to Talk With Iranian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Secretary
Shamshad Ahmad Khan arrived here Saturday morning to discuss with
Iranian officials issues such as Afganistan, terrorism and the
assassination of Iranian nationals in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He will also convey a message from Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif to Iranian President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival, Ahmad Khan expressed hope that during his
two-day stay in Tehran he will be able to "remove any misgivings
or misunderstanding and thereby strengthen the historic friendship
and cooperation between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Khan said there are some misunderstandings between the
two countries and Pakistan has always followed a stable policy
toward Iran based on deep friendship.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and Pakistan cooled down following a
series of assassinations of Iranian citizens in Pakistan and the
killings of eight Iranian diplomats and an Iranian reporter in
Afghanistan by the Pakistan-backed Taliban forces in last August.
</P>
<P>
During the past three years, a number of Iranian citizens were
assassinated in Pakistan. The latest case happened in last
February, in which two Iranian engineers in charge of a bridge
construction project in Karachi were shot dead by unidentified
gunmen.
</P>
<P>
Iran has lodged strong protest to the Pakistani government
over the killings and urged Islamabad to take serious measures to
punish the killers and ensure security for Iranian citizens
living in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister for Asia-Pacific
Affairs Mohsen Aminzadeh said that confidence-building talks are
needed between the two sides in order to restore and maintain
their relations and overcome the misunderstandings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
