<HEADLINE> Zambia Sets 1999 as "Crime Prevention Year" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The year 1999 has been set as "Crime
Prevention year" by the Zambian government , Zambia Daily Mail reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
While announcing the decision, Zambian Home Affairs Permanent Secretary
Joseph Kasongo said at Lusaka's Cathedral of the Holy Cross Friday night
that there could be no meaningful economic development without the
community's political support and operational assistance in crime
prevention.
</P>
<P>
He said that the crime prevention strategy required the integrated
efforts of the police, families, schools, neighborhood associations and
businesses in order to improve the quality of people's lives.
</P>
<P>
However, Kasongo noted that a worrying feature in 1998 was the increase
in violent crimes involving the use of fire arms.
</P>
<P>
And Commissioner of police Silus Ngangula said the police needed to
develop a new relationship with the law abiding people in the community by
allowing them a greater voice in setting local priorities.
</P>
<P>
He said a large proportion of police time and activity are being
channeled to crime prevention due to crimes' impact and consequences on the
general public.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the president of the Crime Prevention Foundation of Zambia,
Francis Musonda, said his organization was committed to making Zambia a
better place to live in by creating safer cities, townships and villages in
order to attract more investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
