<HEADLINE> Feature: More Bangladeshis Show interest in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Islam was one of the Bangladeshi students attending a basic
Chinese learning course, which started here Saturday and was
sponsored by the Dhaka-based Chinese Language Center which
provides both six-month and one-year courses.
</P>
<P>
"As I have seen many Chinese movies and Chinese dramas on TV, I
become very interested in the Chinese language," said Islam, a
student of physics.
</P>
<P>
Unlike Islam, many other students wanted to learn the Chinese
language in order to do business with China, an important trade
partner of the South Asian nation.
</P>
<P>
Trade between China and Bangladesh has been developing fast
during the past few years, which stood at 750 million U.S. dollars
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
M. Rega Iftekhar Patwary, who was pursuing a degree of Master
of Business Administration in the Jahangirnagar University on the
outskirts of Dhaka, said he was thinking of doing business with
China after he finished the MBA program in February this year.
</P>
<P>
"China is a neighboring country of Bangladesh. We want to
establish a friendly relationship with China from which we may
learn a lot of things," he said.
</P>
<P>
Learning the Chinese language was not an easy job for them as
they were amazed by the picture-like Chinese characters, the
writing and pronunciation of which were not integrated as the
Bengali and the English languages.
</P>
<P>
"Learning to speak is easier than learning to write," because
"the pictorial symbols (of the Chinese language) take time to
learn," according to Patwary.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Language Center was established in July 1996 by
F.R. Siddiqui, a Chinese language expert and chemical engineer and
Mannan Khan, who received higher education in China.
</P>
<P>
"With the economic development of China and the increasing
economic cooperation between Bangladesh and China, more and more
Bangladeshis have shown interest in learning Chinese," said Khan.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
