<HEADLINE> Tanzania Inflation Drops to 12.1 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's overall inflation
decreased to 12.1 percent last November from 12.3 percent in the previous
month, according to a latest report from the country's central bank.
</P>
<P>
"The decrease in inflation rate was due to a 0.2 percent decline in non-
food inflation," the central bank said in the newly released November issue
of its monthly economic review.
</P>
<P>
However, facing a nationwide drought, overall inflation is expected to
increase gradually in the coming months on account of upward pressure on
food prices because of short supplies of cereals, especially maize in the
market, said the report.
</P>
<P>
It said that prices of maize, beef and beans have started going up and
the trend is likely to continue.
</P>
<P>
The east African country is short of up to 450,000 tons of food, due to
adverse weather conditions and destructive pests, President Mkapa said in
his New Year message delivered Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
