<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Seven people were killed in Yenagoa,
capital of oil producing Bayelsa State of Nigeria, during confrontations
between Ijaw militant youths known as Egbesu and the government troops, the
Saturday Punch newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
By Friday morning, the paper said, eye witnesses claimed that seven dead
bodies had been discovered in different spots in the state capital.
</P>
<P>
Residents of Yenagoa are fleeing the city in fear of the worsening
situation while soldiers who fled their duty post at the heat of the clash
on Thursday evening returned on Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
Peace of Yenagoa was shattered Wednesday evening when protesting youths
ran into some soldiers stationed at Government House who reportedly opened
fire, killing three of them, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
Angered by the killing, the youths were said to have reinforced to fight
the soldiers later in the evening and four more youths were reported to
have been killed on Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the State Military Administrator, Lieut. Col. Paul Edor Obi
declared a state of emergency in Bayelsa State and imposed a dusk-to-dawn
curfew in the state capital.
</P>
<P>
In his New Year budget broadcast, Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar warned that the government would not tolerate direct
confrontation and would deal decisively with a confrontational stance
adopted by the youths in Ijaw areas.
</P>
<P>
Youths from about 500 communities comprising 40 clans in Ijawland held a
meeting on December 11 in Kaiama and issued a "Kaiama Declaration" in which
they called for among other things the immediate withdrawal of security
forces employed to protect oil installations in the area and stoppage of
all oil exploration and exploitation activities.
</P>
<P>
The Ijaws are demanding the convocation of a sovereign national
conference of ethnic nationalities in the west African country to discuss a
more acceptable means of co-existence.
</P>
<P>
They also want the repeal of the current land use decrees and Petroleum
Act to revert ownership of Ijawland to Ijaws to enable them to manage their
oil resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
