<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Imports Portable Missile Mortars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 2 (Xinhua) - Uganda has imported about 80 tons
of portable missile mortars from Ukraine and Russia, a Tanzanian national
newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Mail said that the convoy of the military hardware has passed
through Tanzania from the northern port of Tanga to Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted reliable sources within the port administration and
military circles as saying that the cargo arrived at Tanga Port two days
before Christmas eve aboard a Greek registered vessel, mv Domain.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources who declined to be named, off-loading started
soon after the ship docked at the port and the arrangements were
immediately made under tight security to transport the goods to Kampala.
</P>
<P>
"What we know is that the goods are now on the way to Uganda by a cargo
train from Tanga-Dar es Salaam-Mwanza-Kampala," the sources added.
</P>
<P>
This is the second large consignment of military hardware since last
November when some 90 tanks imported by Uganda from Ukraine were
transported through Dar es Salaam port and Mwanza to Masaka in southern
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Ministry of Defense and National Service were not immediately
available to comment on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Land-locked Uganda imports goods mainly through Tanzania and its
military supplies are mainly escorted by the Tanzanian military forces.
</P>
<P>
Facing two separate rebellions at home in the north and west, Uganda
has been allegedly backing the rebel army in the neighboring Democratic
Republic of Congo attempting to oust President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania, claiming to be neutral in the DRC conflict, recalled its
military advisors from the DRC almost immediately after the conflict broke
out last August while other neighboring countries rushed their troops to
either side of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
The war has so far already drawn in Angola, Namibia, Chad, Libya, Sudan
and Zimbabwe on Kabila's side while the Tutsi-led rebels are allegedly
backed by Rwanda and Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
