<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Chosen Malaria-Test Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Zambia is among four African
countries which have been selected by the World Health Organization (WHO)
to pre-test a new methodology called "Roll Back Malaria" (RBM) to combat
malaria.
</P>
<P>
James Banda, a WHO consultant based in Geneva and currently in Zambia
to advise on the RBM, said in an interview with Zambia Daily Mail that "the
pre-test results in the four countries will form the basis for finalization
of the methodology to be used by the RBM team to combat malaria the world
over."
</P>
<P>
The newspaper Saturday quoted Banda as saying that the pilot scheme
needed assessment methodology for the RBM which includes Ghana, Nigeria and
Mali, was initiated by the joint forces of the United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF), the United Nations Development Program (UNDP), the World
Bank and the WHO in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
"The four organizations have joined forces to fight malaria under the
RBM program to substantially reduce the human suffering and economic losses
due to malaria," said Banda.
</P>
<P>
Petauke district has been chosen with the support of the Zambian Central
Board of Health, to be the test area in Zambia from December 21, 1998 to
January 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The RBM will seek to strengthen the health systems to ensure better
delivery of health care services especially at district and community
levels and also ensure proper and expanded use of insecticide-treated
mosquito nets.
</P>
<P>
Banda added that the RBM would also ensure adequate access to basic
health care and training of health care workers as well as encourage the
development of simpler and more effective means of administering medicines.
</P>
<P>
This will include training of village health workers, mothers and
drug peddlers on early and appropriate treatment of malaria especially for
children.
</P>
<P>
The RBM will also encourage the development of more effective and new
anti-malaria drugs and vaccines.
</P>
<P>
The pilot scheme is expected to greatly reduce malaria cases and deaths
especially in Africa by the year 2015. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990102.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bomb Blast Destroys Store in Indonesian Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- A strong bomb blast destroyed
the Ramayana Department Store building at Jalan H Agus Salim,
central Jakarta, capital of Indonesia, early Saturday morning,
police said.
</P>
<P>
The explosion, which also shattered the glass walls of a number
of shops near Ramayana, occurred at 5:15 a.m. local time, chief of
the investigation section of the Jakarta Police, Col. Alex Bambang
T said.
</P>
<P>
Police officers found three bombs at the location, "but only
one exploded," Bambang, who inspected the site of the blast, said.
</P>
<P>
He said he could not yet confirm the type and the strength of
the bombs.
</P>
<P>
No casualties were reported.
</P>
<P>
The department store has been closed since it stopped
operations following the widespread riots here in mid-May 1998
during which more than 1,200 people were killed and about 5,000
buildings were destroyed or burned.
</P>
<P>
Da'i Bachtiar, commander of the Indonesian Police's
investigation corps, said security officers have not yet received
reports on who is responsible for the explosion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
