<HEADLINE> Defecting KR Leaders Leave Phnom Penh for Angkor Wat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Khmer Rouge leaders Khieu
Samphan and Nuon Chea, who recently defected to the Cambodian
government, left here Saturday for Siem Reap to visit Angkor Wat,
which was the last stop of their Phnom Penh trip.
</P>
<P>
The pair surrendered to the royal government on December 25
after they got the assurance that they would not be prosecuted.
During their stay in Phnom Penh, they received a warm welcome
from Prime Minister Hun Sen and National Assembly President Prince
Ranariddh.
</P>
<P>
Before they left for Angkor Wat, they also spent two days
sightseeing in the southwest seashore city of Sihanoukville.
</P>
<P>
Khieu Samphan was last seen by the public in 1992 while Nuon
Chea had not appeared since 1979, after the Khmer Rouge went into
a guerrilla war against the government near the Cambodian-Thai
boarder.
</P>
<P>
International and domestic pressures are mounting these days on
the government and Hun Sen to try the two Khmer Rouge leaders. Hun
Sen and King Sihanouk are urged not to pardon the Khmer Rouge
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen responded Friday evening that he is not opposed to the
trial of the Khmer Rouge leaders and the crimes they committed.
"It is a matter of time," he said.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that his position to try the Khmer Rouge has not
changed and will not change.
</P>
<P>
"I did not mention the trial of the Khmer Rouge leaders in my
recent talks not because I have forgotten it, but because I
believed the first thing we should talk about is peace, which is
what the country and the Cambodian people need most," Hun Sen
explained. 
</P>
