<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong Province in South
China last year closed down 21 illegal CD production lines,
confiscated 32.05 million CDs and over 2.5 million books and
magazines in its tough fight against CD piracy.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the province dispatched a total of more than 180,000
people to check some 110,000 shops and stalls in separate raids,
smashed 227 illegal publishing houses and banned 15 black markets
on illegal publications.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong, which borders with Macao and Hong Kong and has a
long coastline, is confronted with active smuggling of illegal
publications. The Customs confiscated 11.27 million pirated
CDs in 1998.
</P>
<P>
One of the biggest cases involved confiscation of over 1.5
million illegal CDs stored in a storage house in Guangzhou City.
