<HEADLINE> Cuba Marks 40th Anniversary of Revolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Cuba on Friday staged a rally in
Santiago to mark the 40th anniversary of the triumph of the Cuban
revolution.
</P>
<P>
Cuban President Fidel Castro, who led the revolution to
victory, returned to the square in Santiago, the second largest
city of the country, where he first appeared as Cuba's leader on
January 1, 1959.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the occasion, Castro said Cuba has made great
progress over the past 40 years. In 1959, only 30 percent of the
population were literate and there were merely four universities
and several dozens of technical schools, but now there are
250,000 teachers who graduated from universities, 64,000 doctors
and 60,000 college graduates in Cuba, the Cuban leader added.
</P>
<P>
Castro praised the Cuban people for their efforts in
overcoming the economic difficulties which have been troubling
the Caribbean island country over the years.
</P>
<P>
He said that for the young Cubans the revolution just began
and they have to carry it on.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban president also criticized the new liberalist
globalization and gave his views over the crisis in the world
economic order and its grave social consequences.
</P>
<P>
A crowd of about 2,000 supporters gathered in the square and
listened to Castro's 90-minute speech with chants of ``Fidel,
Fidel.''
</P>
<P>
At night on January 1, 1959, Castro entered the eastern Cuban
city of Santiago, forcing Dictator Fulgencio Batista to flee Cuba
next morning and throwing down the corrupt Batista regime.
</P>
</TEXT>
