<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Tries to Boost Income of Coco Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Coconut
Administration (PCA) is embarking on a long-term coconut industry
development plan aimed at leading to a 10-fold increase in the
income of coco farmers.
</P>
<P>
In a report published here Saturday, PCA Administrator Eduardo
Escueta said the plan calls for the clustering of small coconut
farm holdings into 15-hectare farm modules called model farms.
</P>
<P>
The business activities in these model farms, according to
Escueta, are expected to raise the income of coco farmers from
10,000 pesos (250 U.S. dollars) per hectare to 100,000 pesos
(2,500 dollars) per hectare yearly.
</P>
<P>
With coconut as the main crop, the model farm concept involves
intensive inter-cropping of short-term cash crops and perennial
tree crops, livestock, poultry raising and aquaculture, he said.
</P>
<P>
Escueta said there are presently 3 million hectares of coconut
land in the Philippines but only about 900,000 hectares are
inter-cropped.
</P>
<P>
Through the model farm program, which the PCA will establish in
selected areas of the country, the PCA hopes to transform small
farm holdings into productive entrepreneurial communities, Escueta
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that while the Philippines still accounts for 73
percent of the total world exports of coconut oil, production is
decreasing because of senility of coconut palms, inadequate seed
gardens for replanting purposes and unabated cutting down of
coconut palms.
</P>
<P>
To remedy the situation, Escueta said, the government is
committed to providing the industry with a minimum annual budget
of 450 million pesos (11 million dollars) after 1999 to continue
the replanting of 50,000 hectares per year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
