<HEADLINE> China's Exports in 1998 Valued at 180 Billion US Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Total exports of China in 1998
were valued at 180 billion U.S. dollars, Zhang Xiang,
Vice-Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC),
has predicted.
</P>
<P>
Speaking recently at a forum marking the 50th anniversary of
the Academy of International Trade and Economic Cooperation under
the MOFTEC, Zhang said exports in 1998 remained almost at the same
level of 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, a final report will be released by China's General
Administration of Customs this month.
</P>
<P>
Zhang also estimated that China's imports in 1998 stood at 135
billion dollars, which means the overall trade volume balanced with
the 1997 figure.
</P>
<P>
Early last year, China planned to achieve a ten percent
increase in foreign trade, but the Asian financial
crisis and severe summer floods in the nation broke its plan.
</P>
<P>
According to Custom statistics, China's trade volume
had accumulated to 286.5 billion U.S. dollars in the first 11
months of 1998, down 0.2 percent from the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In the same period, export volume grew 0.2 percent to reach
163.9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said it was not easy to accomplish this volume,
considering all negative influences in 1998, which featured the
undevaluation of the Chinese currency and economic landslides in
its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Investment contracts from Japan, the Republic of Korea, some
southeast Asian nations, as well as from Hong Kong, Macao and
Taiwan to the motherland dropped 12 percent by the end of
September, while actual used capital going down 10.3 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
