<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Prime Minister Warns of 1999 Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's Prime Minister Phan Van
Khai has urged rural localities nationwide to prepare for
prolonged drought that looms over 1999, casting long shadows over
the next winter-spring and summer-autumn crops.
</P>
<P>
In instructions issued early last week for initiating
anti-drought preparations, Khai said 1998 was a "dry " year and it
could get drier and unpredictable in 1999, hurting agricultural
production, the newspaper Vietnam News reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the rainy season ended about a month earlier than
usual and the total average rainfall dropped by a record 20- to
25-percent against the recent past, according to the General
Department of Meteorology and Hydrology.
</P>
<P>
Water levels have fallen by 20 to 40 percent and flash floods
recorded their lowest incidence since 1926, particularly in the
Mekong River delta.
</P>
<P>
There is already a severe shortage of water supply for staple,
industrial and cash crops in many areas of Vietnam which has and
will continue to adversely affect the life and production of
farmers, the prime minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
