<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Old Friends Move Closer by Fresh Visits (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan kicked off his five-African-nation tour this morning,
marking a fresh start for enhancing relations with old friends
in the continent.
</P>
<P>
The visit, China's first diplomatic activity in the new year,
demonstrates the great importance the country places on the
Sino-African relations.
</P>
<P>
The five countries -- Egypt, Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania and
Zambia -- enjoy long-standing and stable cooperative relations
with China.
</P>
<P>
Sources say that duing the visit Tang will confer with the
leaders of the five nations on furthering the growth of bilateral
relations, the regional situation and other issues of mutual
concern.
</P>
<P>
Liu Guijin, director of the African Affairs Department in the
Chinese Foreign Ministry, told Xinhua that China will not neglect
its ties with Africa while it improves its relations with
powers.
</P>
<P>
Liu, who is accompanying Tang on the visit, said he believes
this tour will instill new impetus into the continuing and smooth
growth of Sino-African relations, especially the cooperation in a
variety of areas between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Tang, who took office last March, is following the tradition of
his predecessor by choosing Africa as the destination of the first
visit in a year.
</P>
<P>
Africa was the first place visited by Vice-Premier Qian Qichen
at the beginning of a year during his ten-year term as China's
foreign minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
