<DOCNO> XIE19990102.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Friends Move Closer by Fresh Visits (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Moreover, Tang began his first official visit to five nations
in west Africa last June, and his ongoing Africa tour, across the
rest of the continent, demonstrates China's willingness to enhance
traditional Sino-African friendship by pursuing consistent
policies toward Africa.
</P>
<P>
Sino-African relations have gone well in recent years. Chinese
President Jiang Zemin put forward a five-point proposal for
advancing long-standing, stable, cooperative and comprehensive
relations geared to the 21st century during his 1996 six-African
nation tour, which gained wide popularity in the continent.
</P>
<P>
After Jiang's Africa tour, then Chinese Premier Li Peng also
paid a visit to seven African nations in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The two visits fully show that China values traditional
Sino-African friendship, and is prepared to enhance its political
and economic relations.
</P>
<P>
Since then, South Africa, Niger, the Central African Republic
and Guinea-Bissau established or restored diplomatic relations
with China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Customs statistics show that bilateral trade volume in
the January-November period last year stood at approximately 5
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
There exists enormous untapped potential for cooperation in
technology, equipment and natural resources exploitation made
possible by highly complementary economies of the two sides.
</P>
<P>
As world multipolarization moves forward, the further
growth of Sino-African friendship and cooperation will not only
help safeguard the rights and interests of the developing
countries, but also establish a new international order,
local analysts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
