<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to regulate Foreign Trade in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's Prime Minister Phan Van
Khai has asked relevant ministries to regulate next year's imports
and exports based on the balance of payments, Vietnam News Agency
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Under a decision which was issued by the prime minister on
December 30 and will be in effect from January 1, 1999, to March
31, 2000, a number of commodities will be subject to import
regulation.
</P>
<P>
They include electric fans, ceramic and granite tiles, consumer
goods made of porcelain, glass and pottery, packages made of
finished plastics, steel tubes of 20-114 mm, cast-iron tubes,
bicycles, refined vegetable oil, trucks of fewer than five tons,
passenger buses of 15 to 50 seats, cargo and passenger
automobiles, second-hand ambulances.
</P>
<P>
The import of consumer goods and some materials, including
steel ingots, PVC, aluminum bars and components will be regulated
by taxes and additional charges.
</P>
<P>
Importers of consumer goods have to balance their foreign
currency sources and make prompt payments in cash, according to
the decision.
</P>
<P>
The Trade Ministry will be responsible for conducting
negotiations for a reasonable balance of two-way trade turnover
with those countries which want to export a large volume of goods
to Vietnam at the latter's preferential tariffs, the decision
said.
</P>
<P>
The government will ensure foreign currency for importing
petroleum, fertilizer and iron and steel, which will be allowed
for re-export only when foreign customers can make repayment in
convertible foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister will make a final decision if the countries
sharing borders with Vietnam officially ask to buy the said
materials but are unable to pay in convertible foreign currencies.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
