<HEADLINE> Philippines to Improve Fire Service in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
promised Saturday to make its effort to fully improve the fire
service nationwide.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview Saturday, Undersecretary Ronaldo Puno of
the Department of Interior and Local Government (DILG) said the
planned devolution would pass on the maintenance and operation
expenses from the national to the local government.
</P>
<P>
"This won't be like the devolution in 1992 when the DILG
devolved only personnel but not the finances," Puno said.
</P>
<P>
Puno also said his office is now studying the capacity of local
governments to shoulder the cost of fire-prevention and
fire-response programs.
</P>
<P>
He said that while local governments have more than enough
resources for the purpose, most lack the financial capability to
do so.
</P>
<P>
"Perhaps in about 60 percent of our country, they really do not
have the financial capacity to absorb the services," he said.
</P>
<P>
The inadequacy of the fire service's ability to respond
properly to fires surfaced anew on December 3, 1998, when a
pre-dawn fire burned down an orphanage in Paco, Manila, killing at
least 30 persons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
