<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-CORRECTS dateline S.Korea's Trade Surplus Hit 39.9 Billion U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 2 (Xinhua) -- South Korea registered a trade
surplus of 39.9 billion U.S. dollars in 1998, said the Commerce,
Industry and Energy Ministry Saturday.
</P>
<P>
South Korean export reached 133.22 billion dollars, down 2.2
percent from 1997 while import plunged 35.4 billion dollars to
93.34 billion dollars, said the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus almost hit the target of 40 billion dollars
set by the South Korean government earlier last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South Korea's per capita gross national product
(GNP) is expected to plunge by 33.5 percent to 6,321 dollars in
1998 following the financial crisis, which was caused primarily
by corporate bankruptcies and bad loans of financial institutions
in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, economists said the worst time of the financial
crisis has gone though South Korea's per capita is due to rank
42nd in the world in 1998, down from 34th in 1997.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's economy will emerge from slump in the first
quarter of 1999 on improved domestic sales, export and corporate
profitability, said the Bank of Korea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
