<HEADLINE> 9 Killed in Canada Avalanche </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Nine people were killed and 25
injured by an avalanche in northern Quebec of Canada early
Friday, reports said, raising the previous toll of eight.
</P>
<P>
The tragedy struck at about midnight Friday as some 400 to 500
people were packed into the school gym of an Inuit village
celebrating the New Year.
</P>
<P>
Six people died soon after the avalanche crashed into the gym,
while three other victims were discovered several hours later,
buried deep under mounds of snow, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Twelve of the injured were flown by jet-air ambulance to
Montreal hospitals. Others were treated at the village of
Kangiqsualujjuaq, which is about 1,500 kilometers northeast of
Montreal.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, there was a big storm, which caused the avalanc
he," Marc Lavallee, a spokesman for Quebec's civil security
department, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Some party-goers said they believed a New Year's Eve gun
salute triggered loose snow from the hill, which is about 300
meters from the school gym. 
</P>
</TEXT>
