<DOCNO> XIE19990102.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Philippines Deepens Banking Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- With the financial sector being a
liability in its effort to revive the economy, the Philippines
introduced a package of banking reform measures at the end of last
year to gain the upper hand in facing the challenges in 1999.
</P>
<P>
As the government projected the country's gross domestic
product to grow by 2.1 percent to 3.1 percent this year, the
Manila-based Asia Development Bank warned that the economy would
be hard-pressed to reach the target.
</P>
<P>
In its annual Country Economic Review, the bank said a critical
factor affecting the economy's ability to recover quickly will be
the pace at which the health of the banking sector can be
restored.
</P>
<P>
The bank noted that the ratio of bad loans to total
outstanding loans in the country's banking system rose to 10.5
percent last August from a pre-crisis level of 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Wall Street Journal quoted some economists as
predicting that the ratio would jump to 15 percent in the coming
months.
</P>
<P>
Problems in the country's banking system could pose a threat
to the country's effort for economic recovery, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
As part of the government's drive to weed out weak banks and
improve transparency, the Central Bank of the Philippines last
month deepened reform on the country's 53 big banks, 20 of which
are universal banks and 33 commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
The central bank required the banks to raise their
capitalization by a December 24 deadline, prescribing a
2-billion-peso (50-million-U.S. dollar) capital level for
commercial banks and a 4.5-billion-peso (113-million-dollar) level
for universal banks.
</P>
<P>
As a result, 49 of the banks got the nod with enough funds to
guard against likely future financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The four banks that failed to shore up their capital were
required to execute a memorandum of understanding with the central
bank on a capital restoration plan.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, the banks must upgrade their capital position
within 30 days, or face sanctions, which include prohibition of
payment of cash dividends, stripping of branching privilege and
denial of access to the central bank's rediscounting facilities.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said it would strictly monitor the operation
of the four banks through special examinations and frequent
meetings with their board of directors.
</P>
<P>
These measures are aimed at improving transparency concerning
the capital of the banks and the operation of the weak banks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Monetary Board, the policy-making body of the
central bank, has approved in principle the application of
Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corp. for a license to operate as a
universal bank in the country.
</P>
<P>
Given the emerging capital markets worldwide and Hongkong
Bank's overseas network and technological expertise, Hongkong Bank
could be instrumental in exposing the Philippine capital market to
international investors.
</P>
<P>
Hongkong Bank has been operating in the Philippines since 1875
and is one of the largest banking and financial services
organizations in the world.
</P>
<P>
It would be the second foreign bank to operate as a universal
bank in the country, with ING Bank being the first to get a
universal bank license.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the central bank is making great effort to seek
international aid to directly fund the banking reform.
</P>
<P>
For example, a World Bank loan, which is still under
negotiation, is designed to finance reforms in the banking sector
especially in the area of bank supervision and examination,
government officials said.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund, on the other hand, will
provide balance-of-payments support to ensure the country's
credit worthiness and as protection against currency speculators,
they added.
</P>
<P>
As pointed out by the government officials, although the ratio
of bad loans to total outstanding loans in the country's banking
system is manageable compared with that of other countries of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations, the financial system needs
to be strengthened in the country's effort to achieve economic
recovery.
</P>
<P>
In addition, around 40 banks in the country closed down during
the past year.
</P>
<P>
The banks in the Philippines ushered in the new year by
embracing reform, which they hope will enable them to take up the
challenges in the new year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990102.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Security: Uganda Rises to the Challenge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's road of development
in 1998 proved extraordinarily arduous and bumpy with security
looming as a growing problem.
</P>
<P>
With liberalization of the economy in the east African
country, terrorism, though still a new phenomenon in Uganda, has
become increasingly rampant as the Ugandans were haunted by the
hair-raising acts of terrorism throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
In early April, two terrorist bombings in downtown Kampala
killed four innocent diners and evoked a tense atmosphere among
panic-gripped residents.
</P>
<P>
On May 18, Uganda's biggest city robbery in the year occurred
when a gang of five armed thugs broke into the Cairo
International Bank in broad daylight and got away with 240,000
U.S. Dollars. Two other bank robberies that followed forced
bankers to beef up security.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 rebels of the Allied Democratic Forces (ADF) launched
a pre-dawn surprise attack on Kichwamba National Technical
Institute in western Uganda in early June, burning more than 80
sleeping students to death and abducting more than 100 others.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that more than 360 children have been abducted
by ADF rebels since 1996 and much more by rebels of Lord's
Resistance Army (LRA) in the North.
</P>
<P>
These two rebel groups, using bases on foreign land, sneak
into Uganda from time to time and kill and maim local residents,
making life in northern and western border districts a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
The capital city, Kampala, was also targeted by terrorists in
early August when devastating bombings in Nairobi and
Dar-es-Salaam shocked the world. The schemes were, fortunately,
not implemented because they were found in time.
</P>
<P>
The three explosions on buses bound for up-country, which
killed 30 passengers on August 25, plus the reports of LRA rebels
ambushing buses on feeder roads in distant districts made
highways roads of danger for many.
</P>
<P>
Terrorists also target foreigners. A dozen people including
Chinese, South Koreans and Americans have been killed in Kampala
alone in the past year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, several foreign embassies and U.N. agencies here
received threats and had to closed temporarily for safety's sake.
</P>
<P>
The growing insecurity has incurred heavy losses to local
people and it has become a huge stumbling stone hampering the
country's social and economic development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990102.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Security: Uganda Rises to the Challenge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tourism and foreign investment are sectors first and worst hit
by deteriorating security.
</P>
<P>
Tourist arrivals plummeted to about 50,000 this year from the
150,000 in 1997, due to security concerns.
</P>
<P>
The tourist regions of Kasese, Kabarole and Bundibugyo
districts in the west and some districts in the north experienced
disruptions due to insecurity.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more and more foreign investors, who used to choose
Uganda as an investment destination, tend to revise their
decisions. In 1997, foreign investment in the country topped 1.5
billion U.S. Dollars while only one fifth of that amount was
registered in the first 11 months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Lack of foreign exchange caused by the shrinking tourism and
capital withdrawal by foreign investors has made local currency
extremely weak, with Ugandan shilling depreciated by more than 20
percent against U.S. Dollar from August to December in 1998. And
the Shilling is still falling as the state coffers does not have
enough hard currency to inject into the market to rescue the
falling Shilling.
</P>
<P>
The frequent cases of terrorism have also tarnished the image
of the government, as people's confidence in the government is
weakened and donors, whose money the country depends so heavily
on, find the government losing control of the situation.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has been deemed a success story both economically and
politically in Africa. But all this economic revival and relative
stability, achieved after long-time efforts by the ruling
National Resistance Movement government, can be stifled in the
cradles by unchecked terrorism.
</P>
<P>
To safeguard all these hard-earned achievements, Uganda is now
doubling its efforts to fight against terrorism and other crimes.
</P>
<P>
In the new budget, the military spending increased by 26
percent to improve the army's capability through modernization.
The Defense Ministry has imported new military hardware to equip
the army.
</P>
<P>
State Minister of Defense Steven Kavuma said last month Uganda
is building a modernized, highly disciplined army to defend its
borders against any incursions by rebels as well as aggressors.
</P>
<P>
Police are also reinforced. A total of 1,000 new recruits were
made recently and more people will be added to the police force.
</P>
<P>
Following the surge of terrorism, more policemen were sent on
patrol in streets and more security operations were conducted.
Meanwhile, police training has resumed after several years of
neglect.
</P>
<P>
Local media have also been mobilized to boost the security
awareness among average Ugandans.
</P>
<P>
However, burdened with a heavy foreign debt of 3.6 billion
U.S. Dollars, the Ugandan government can not expect to
eliminate poverty overnight, which is regarded as a key source
of crime and terrorism. Security, therefore, is and may
continue to be a big challenge for the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990102.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
