<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Hold City Polls in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Elections in Bangladesh's four
city corporations and 147 municipalities will be held in the last
week of February, The Daily Star newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Election Commission would announce the poll schedules
before the Eid-ul-Fitr, likely to be observed on January 20 after
the Ramadan, the month of fasting.
</P>
<P>
"We are planning to hold the mayoral polls as well as the
municipal elections in the last week of February," Chief Election
Commissioner Mohammad Abu Hena was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The three-member Election Commission, a constitutional body in
charge of the country's elections, would hold a meeting on Sunday
to finalize the election schedules.
</P>
<P>
Elections in the 147 municipalities would be staged over three
days and the mayoral polls would be held on a single day, the
newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The mayoral polls had been scheduled to take place by April 3
this year. The municipal polls were due in February last year but
could not be held because of a writ petition against a certain
amendment to the electoral law.
</P>
<P>
Under the amended provision, the government would enjoy the
right to appoint a bureaucrat to run the municipalities for the
period between the expiry of the tenure of an elected body and the
takeover by another elected body.
</P>
<P>
The Association of the Municipal Chairmen called the provision
unconstitutional and submitted a writ petition to the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
The last municipal polls in Bangladesh were held on January 30,
1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
