<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Total Births Dip in Singapore in Tiger Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Fewer babies were born in
Singapore in 1998, the Year of the Tiger which many Chinese here
consider an inauspicious year, the local English newspaper The
Straits Times reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The paper said 26,534 babies were born to Chinese fathers in
the first 11 months of 1998, nearly 2,800 fewer than the previous
year's 29,323.
</P>
<P>
The dip is not mirrored in the other ethnic groups in
Singapore, the paper noted.
</P>
<P>
The paper said there was a similar fall in the number of babies
born in the last Tiger Year in 1986 which saw about 4,000 fewer
born than in the preceding year, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by Singapore Immigration and Registration
show 40,388 babies were born in Singapore in the first 11 months
of 1998, about 2,500 fewer than the 42,963 born in the same period
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The paper attributed the drop in the birth rate to the belief by
many Chinese here that Tiger babies, especially girls, will grow
up with fierce temperaments.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that many appear to have avoided starting
their family in the Year of Tiger, preferring perhaps to wait for
the Year of the Rabbit.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the traditional beliefs, the paper quoted a young
mother of two children as saying, "But really, a lot of it is just
traditional beliefs. There is little proof that it is true."
</P>
<P>
The woman, 29 in age, has a boy born in September 1998, who
is nowhere as "fierce' and active as his sister who was born three
years ago in the Year of the Rat.
</P>
<P>
Overall, however, the birth rate in Singapore has been
declining over the past decades. Live births hit a high of 62,495
in 1958 and had been sliding steadily since then to 47,333 in
1997, the paper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
