<DOCNO> XIE19990102.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Mergers, Acquisitions Hit Record in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 1 (Xinhua) -- With more than 7,700
transactions and announced values totaling 1.2 trillion U.S.
dollars, the merger and acquisition (M&AMP;A) market in the United
States broke its previous records in 1998, a report said Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to Mergerstat, a division of Los Angeles investment
bank Houlihan Lockey Howard &AMP; Zukin, the previous all-time record
was set in 1997, with 650.7 billion dollars in value. Although
the number of deals was basically even with 1997, the average
transaction size of last year was 393.7 million dollars, up 88
percent.
</P>
<P>
The increase in average deal size was fueled by increases in
both the number and size of mega-deals valued at one billion
dollars and above, said Mergerstat, which tracks deals involving
U.S. companies. Mega-mergers accounted for almost 920 billion
dollars and 77 percent of the total M&AMP;A deal market.
</P>
<P>
For the second consecutive year, financial services industry
led the market, with deals involving banks, brokerages,
investment firms and insurance companies accounting for 25.4
percent of all announced deals. Four of the top deals were in the
financial services sector, including the NationsBank acquisition
of BankAmerica and Travelers Group's acquisition of Citicorp.
</P>
<P>
The highly active telecommunications industry helped drive
communications to the number two industry ranking, with deals
accounting for 170 billion dollars and 14.3 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Oil and gas was third with 12.9 percent of the 1998 deal
market and transactions valued at 154.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The last two of the top five industries were utilities and
broadcasting, each with about a five-percent share of the overall
deal value. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990102.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Govt. to Invest in New Power Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government will
invest over 1.6 billion rupees (23.5 million U.S. dollars) in new
power projects this year to meet the demand from households and
the industrial sector, government officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 100 million rupees (1.47 million dollars) will be
spent this year on setting up new transformers and expanding
electricity supply, said Ananda Dharmapriya, senior assistant
secretary with the Ministry of Irrigation, Power and Energy.
</P>
<P>
He said Sri Lanka has decided to observe 1999-2009 as a decade
of power development.
</P>
<P>
The 10-year power development program, estimated to cost 200
billion rupees (2.94 billion dollars), is designed to provide
every household with electricity and increase the national power
grid in order to cater to upcoming industries.
</P>
<P>
Several coal-fired or hydro power projects are expected to be
launched during the 10-year period, said the secretary.
</P>
<P>
Only 52 percent of Sri Lankan households have access to
electricity at present. The power shortage has severely restricted
the scope of people's life and industrial development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
