<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Attracts 1.9 Bln Dollars of Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam attracted a total of 1.9
billion U.S. dollars of foreign investment in 1998, the Vietnam
News Saturday quoted a government official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Deputy minister of planning and investment Nguyen Nhac said it
was "a remarkable result in view of the negative impacts of the
regional financial and monetary crisis on the country."
</P>
<P>
However, he did not say how many foreign investment funds had
been disbursed.
</P>
<P>
Some 70 percent of foreign investment capital into Vietnam had
come from Asian counties which have been affected by the ongoing
regional financial crisis. The countries also accounted for 70
percent of Vietnam's exports.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the number of projects and the amount of foreign
investment into Vietnam in 1998 dropped by 21.5 percent and 10.1
percent over 1997 respectively, said the official.
</P>
<P>
Foreign invested projects accounted for about 23.5 percent of
the national industrial value last year compared with 20.6 percent
in 1997 and 21.4 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 270,000 Vietnamese people were working in foreign
invested projects that contributed 320 million U.S. dollars to the
state budget, an increase of 1.6 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
To improve the environment for foreign investors, the
Vietnamese government has lowered land rent for 269 projects in
four industrial zones in Hanoi, Haiphong and Ho Chi Minh city.
</P>
</TEXT>
