</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990102.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Video Film Production Becomes More Brisk in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, January 2 (Xinhua) -- The output of video films was
much greater than that of motion pictures in Myanmar in 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, only 15 new Myanmar motion
pictures were produced, while there were 547 video films.
</P>
<P>
There are 7,202 entrepreneurs who are engaged in the business
of video halls, while there are only 160 cinemas in the country.
</P>
<P>
The production of video films grows rapidly because of high
demand for videos.
</P>
<P>
In order to properly control and manage the video industry, the
Myanmar Ministry of Information revised in December some video
rules under the existing 1996 Television and Video Law, revoking
some television and video procedures.
</P>
<P>
The Video Censor Board was formed to check the films and videos
in accordance with the policies, rules and standards to make sure
they are found suitable to be shown to the public. 
</P>
