<HEADLINE> Indonesian Minister Admits Gov't Puts Sports on Back Burner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian State Minister of
Youth Affairs and Sports Agung Laksono conceded the government's
attention to national sports is lacking and much needs to be done
to polish the professionalism of coaches and athletes.
</P>
<P>
During an evaluation of the past year in national sports,
Agung said politics and the economic crisis were the government's
priorities.
</P>
<P>
"You know that in the decrees of the People's Consultative
Assembly, sports were not involved even in the reform era. We
don't even have the sports law although it was discussed several
years ago," Agung was quoted by the Jakarta Post as saying on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Agung expressed hope new members of the House of
Representatives from the general election in June could use their
initiative rights for the sports law.
</P>
<P>
"Even if we don't have it now, we shouldn't be pessimistic
and desperate," he added.
</P>
<P>
Agung said the next government must pay more attention to
sports. He also hoped for an end to all political and economic t
urmoil to enable the sports community to focus on their
international challenges.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has launched the Golden Garuda project to groom
young athletes for the Asiad, with an aim to finish at least
sixth in the quadrennial event.
</P>
<P>
In the 13th Asian Games in Bangkok in December, Indonesia
finished 11th with six golds, 10 silvers and 11 bronzes.
</P>
<P>
It was double the number of Indonesian golds won at the Asiad
in Hiroshima, Japan. All those medals were earned in badminton.
</P>
<P>
"If we look at the golds, our achievement has improved 100
percent, but if the basis is on our ranking, we are still far
behind other Asian countries and regions, including Thailand,"
Agung said.
</P>
<P>
"If the chaotic situation continues, I guess it will be a
threat to the Golden Garuda project," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister urged each sports organization to identify its
strengths for major events.
</P>
<P>
"In track and field, we've proved that our best is in the
middle distance running events. We must urge athletes not only
to win the gold, but also to set a new record, either Asian or
world", he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the National Sports Council's goal prioritization
could extend to sending younger or second-string athletes to
events such as the Southeast Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
"Of course, we always want to win, but we must understand
which event we should compete in. If our Asiad gold medalists
have to compete in the Southeast Asian Games, it wouldn't make
sense anymore," he said.
</P>
<P>
Agung said the council should also strive to enhance the skil
ls of coaches to draw out top performances from their charges.
</P>
<P>
He urged the council's provincial branches to more actively
hone athletes for national training camps.
</P>
<P>
Agung said the council should build an international-standard
sports complex outside the capital but close to a university
campus if it was sincere about hosting the Asiad. He cited the
University of Indonesia campus as a possibility.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, it seems more likely that neighbouring
Malaysia, host of the Commonwealth Games, and India will bid for
the Asiad.
</P>
<P>
"The problem in building such a complex is funds. It's
impossible to use the Senayan complex as it's really crowded," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"If we can't provide such facilities, we must wait for
another four years to host an Asiad," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
