<HEADLINE> Thai Scientists Plan to Clone Elephants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 2 (Xinhua) ---- Thai scientists have initiated
a project to clone elephants whose number is dwindling in
Thailand, the Bangkok Post reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The project, initiated by scientists at Mahidol University's
Institute of Science and Technology for Research and Development,
would be a long-term one to be carried out over the next 10 years,
veterinarian Chisanu Chiyacharoensri was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Elephant is Thailand's national symbol. However, there has been
a decline in the number of Thai elephants. As a result, there are
now very few elephants with good physical characteristics left in
the country, especially hulks with beautiful long tusks.
</P>
<P>
After learning of foreign scientists' attempt to clone the
extinct mammoth, their Thai counterparts who believed it would be
possible to clone Thai elephants launched a basic research program
starting with a study of life cycle of five female elephants that
would take about four years to complete.
</P>
<P>
Thai scientists at Mahidol University had already achieved
partial success in their project to clone a cow, which was
pregnant at the moment. This would be a good foundation for the
elephant-cloning project, the vet said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
