<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Official Predicts War Over Water Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 1 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations
environmental official predicted a possible war over water as a
result of an increasing conflict between population and water
resources.
</P>
<P>
Klaus Toepfer, Director-General of the United Nations Environ
ment Program, said in an interview that appeared in the Friday
issue of Environmental Science and Technology that he was
convinced there would be a conflict over natural resources,
particularly water.
</P>
<P>
He said: "Everybody knows that we have an increase in
population, but we do not have a corresponding increase in
drinking water, so the result in the regional dimension is
conflict."
</P>
<P>
He called for efforts to monitor worldwide reserves of
drinking water and establish cooperative agreements for the use
of water, including groundwater. He also urged economic
instruments to stimulate the use of new technologies to promote
water conservation.
</P>
<P>
Predicting a dramatic global population growth in the future,
Toepfer called for an "efficiency revolution." He said any
solution for addressing the growth must be linked with "new
technologies that concentrate more on efficient use of limited
natural resources."
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said these technologies must be available on
preferential terms to developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
