<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso vowed to build a more unified and just Brazil as he
officially started his second four-year term on the first day of
1999.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before the National Congress after being sworn in,
Cardoso said Brazil "would not have much merit being the eighth
world economy if we continue to lead in social inequality."
</P>
<P>
He noted that 10 percent of the country's richest households
control 50 percent of the nation's wealth, while the poor 50
percent of the population earns only 10 percent of the national
wealth. In the countryside, nearly 20 percent of the population
holds 88 percent of the land, while the poorest 40 percent of the
population owns just one percent.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso reaffirmed that he will fulfill the commitments made
during his election campaign to improve the distribution of
wealth, to maintain the stability of the Brazilian currency, and
to create more jobs.
</P>
<P>
He said that he will "continue to construct a stable, modern,
open, and competitive economy" and push ahead reforms in the
social security, administration, tax, political and judicial
systems.
</P>
<P>
The president also underscored the importance of dialogue with
the opposition, saying that "dialogue contributes to identify new
truths, enriches democracy, and strengthens the country."
</P>
<P>
Cardoso won the presidential election on October 4 to become
the republic's first president re-elected to a second term.
