<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Economy Shrinks Over 13 Percent in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's economy shrank by
13.68 percent in 1998, and may contract by 2 percent to 1.5
percent depending on the political situation at home, according to
the Central Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
"We expect the economy to grow 1.5 percent in the fiscal year
ending March 2000, depending on the political situation. If the
general election in June and the presidential selection in
November do not proceed smoothly, the economy could contract by 2
percent," bureau chairman Sugito Suwito was quoted by the
Indonesian Observer Saturday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the strengthening of the rupiah in the last three
months of the year, the 1998 figure is better than the earlier
forecast of a 15 percent economic contraction made by the
government and the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, year-on-year inflation stood at 77.63 percent in
December, lower than November's 78.15 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the same period of 1997, inflation was recorded at 11.05
percent.
</P>
<P>
"For inflation, the best we can expect (in 1999) is about 15
percent, and this also depends on our political condition.
Disruption to the political timetable could boost it to 20
percent," Sugito said.
</P>
<P>
Sugito said the bureau expects the 1998 trade surplus to almost
double to 22.63 billion U.S. dollars, up from 11.74 billion U.S.
dollars in the previous year because of plummeting imports due to
the rupiah depreciation against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
He said exports in 1998 are estimated at 50.06 billion U.S.
dollars, 6.3 percent lower than 53.44 billion U.S. dollars in
1997. Imports are seen at 27.4 billion U.S. dollars, a 34 percent
drop against 41.68 billion U.S. dollars in the previous year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
