<HEADLINE> Foreman-Holmes Fight Called Off (update) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The bout between
ex-heavyweight champions George Foreman and Larry Homes,
scheduled for January 23 at the Houston Astrodome, was called off
Friday, according to Foreman's brother.
</P>
<P>
"George says it's off," Roy Foreman said, adding that
promoter Roger Levitt did not meet the deadline for paying
Foreman the remaining $9 million of his $10 million purse.
</P>
<P>
"They were supposed to have the money last week and they
didn't have it," Roy Foreman said. "George gave them an extra
week and they still didn't have it."
</P>
<P>
Holmes said:"I don't know what's going on."
</P>
<P>
The match intended to bring Foreman, 50, and Holmes, 49, to
fight. The combined age of the fighters was believed to be the
highest in boxing history. Holmes' career record is 66-6 and
Foreman's 76-5.
</P>
<P>
The fight was in trouble a week ago when one of its major
sponsors pulled out. On Thursday, promoter Levitt said he was
going through "financial machinations" with the two fighters and
that the letters of credit would be deposited by Monday.
</P>
<P>
Foreman received a nonrefundable $1 million deposit and
Holmes has got $400,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990102.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Welcomes Euro But Some Doubt It </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 1 (Xinhua) -- With the stroke of midnight Friday
to Saturday, the new common currency euro start to be used by some
290 million people in 11 countries in European. Germany welcomes
euro coming.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, the seat of the European Central Bank(ECB),
thousands watched at the night of Friday a huge digital clock count
down the seconds remaining until the birth of "Euroland" - the
euro currency zone reaching from Finland to southern Italy and
France's overseas territories in the Caribbean, South America and
the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
While millions across the continent were greeting the New Year
at parties, thousands of European finance sector employees were
already busy converting computer programs for the new currency.
</P>
<P>
When financial markets re-open around the world on Monday, they
will have to cope with the new currency of "Euroland" - a
commercial zone with almost one-fifth of the world's gross
domestic product.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, Germany's financial center, the start of the
monetary union was celebrated with light shows and a fireworks
display at midnight.
</P>
<P>
High-rise buildings in the financial center on the Main river
known as "Mainhattan" were decorated with the euro symbol. The
euro symbol, "e", was created by turning on lights in some offices
and leaving others darkened.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday's afternoon, over 13,000 people in front of the
building of the ECB-headquarter in Frankfurt composed a great
human symbol of the euro, to welcome the euro starting.
</P>
<P>
But some German respondent remained sceptical about the euro.
In a poll by the German Emnid polling organization, only 51
percent of 1,000 people questioned said they thought the euro was
a good idea.
</P>
<P>
In front of the building of ECZ, an old man said the euro
coming is happening too quickly. There were many problem which
were not resolved. He worried about the euro not to be stable and
strong like D-Mark.
</P>
<P>
But younger people were more optimistic. Some said, they were
happy that euro starts. It will lead to a new era in European, at
least we don't need making the headache to exchange money when we
travel in the euro-zone.
</P>
<P>
Eleven countries of the EU belong to the euro-zone. Britain,
Denmark and Sweden decided against adopting the euro in the "first
wave". Greece failed to meet the strict fiscal criteria for the
single currency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
